    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="750"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d750">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.114 Narcotics/934</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 3178</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-07">December 7,
                            1934</date>.<lb/>[Received December 28.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Legation’s
                    despatch No. 2860 of July 21, 1934,<note n="84" xml:id="d750fn84">Not
                        printed.</note> concerning the question of permitting Chinese officials to
                    search American naval vessels for suspected shipments of contraband narcotics,
                    and to enclose herewith a copy of despatch L. No. 608 of December 3, 1934,<note
                        n="84" xml:id="d750fn1">Not printed.</note> from the Consulate General at
                    Hankow concerning a case that developed in connection with the smuggling of
                    morphine by Chinese members of the crew of the U.S.S. <hi rend="italic"
                        >Tutuila</hi>.</p>
                <p>It will be observed that morphine was actually discovered by the ship’s officers
                    in their search, but that, although Admiral Wainwright<note n="85"
                        xml:id="d750fn85">Rear Adm. John D. Wainwright, commanding the Yangtze
                        Patrol, U. S. Asiatic Fleet.</note> and Consul Stanton<note n="86"
                        xml:id="d750fn86">Edwin F. Stanton, Consul at Hankow.</note> in accordance
                    with the established policy refused to permit Chinese officials to be present
                    during the process of search, the latter apparently were satisfied with the
                    efforts made and did not seem inclined to press their request that they should
                    personally be in attendance at the investigations.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">C. E. Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
